{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474307"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.19,0.23,0.24,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4565"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84771"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"797"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35712"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic in a remote country town with a 10-day history of left hip pain. His parents have noticed that he favours his affected leg when walking. He was born at term without complications and has met all developmental milestones. His growth is progressing appropriately. He has no significant medical history and has not been unwell recently. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild tenderness on palpation of the left hip, and he has an antalgic gait favouring the left side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of the hip and pelvis is performed in a neighbouring town 30 minutes away. The digital images are reviewed by a radiologist in a tertiary centre and reported as normal. The nearest rural medical centre with CT and MRI facilities is a four-hour drive away for the family.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigating this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan","MRI","Ultrasound","Reassurance","Repeat X-ray in two weeks"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is classic for Legg-Calve-Perthes disease, a condition of unknown cause in which there is osteonecrosis of the femoral head. It typically presents as hip pain and/or limp, more commonly in male children between 3-10 years of age, with an acute onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOften, plain radiographs return a normal result early in the disease progression. In an ideal setting, the next investigation would be an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E scan, as this has the highest sensitivity for the condition. However, given the remote setting described in the stem, the most applicable and realistic option in this scenario is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat X-ray in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. By this time, the radiologist in the tertiary centre would hopefully be able to identify any early radiographic evidence of disease progression sufficient to make a formal diagnosis, such as joint space widening and subchondral fracture. At this stage, the need for an MRI scan may become more apparent and justified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scans\u003C/strong\u003E deliver a higher radiation dose to the patient and are not as sensitive for the condition as MRI, hence this is not the correct answer in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E scans should be used as an adjunct to other imaging modalities. While it may be able to diagnose the disease later in its progression, early in the disease course there are only non-specific findings such as joint effusion. These may aid in the diagnosis of Legg-Calve-Perthes disease but cannot diagnose it outright.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect here. Paediatric musculoskeletal issues, particularly hip problems, should be taken seriously due to the potential complications such as degenerative joint disease in adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of considering practical constraints in rural and remote settings when making diagnostic decisions. While MRI remains the gold standard for early diagnosis of Legg-Calve-Perthes disease, a pragmatic approach using serial X-rays can be an appropriate alternative when advanced imaging is not readily accessible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the description of the boy \u0022favouring his affected leg\u0022 means he is trying to reduce weight-bearing on the painful left hip. This results in an antalgic gait pattern where he spends less time in the stance phase on the affected (left) side to minimize pain. This is a protective mechanism and a common clinical finding in children with hip pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["MRI is the most sensitive investigation for early-stage Legg-Calve-Perthes disease, but may not always be practical in rural settings.","Plain radiographs may be normal in the early stages of Legg-Calve-Perthes disease.","Repeat X-rays after a short interval can be useful in diagnosing Legg-Calve-Perthes disease when more advanced imaging is not readily available."],"references":["Wenger DR, Ward WT, Herring JA. Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease. J Bone Joint Surg Am. 1991 Jun;73(5):778-88. PMID: 2045406.","Ibrahim T, Little DG. The Pathogenesis and Treatment of Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes Disease. JBJS Rev. 2016 Jul 19;4(7):e4. doi: 10.2106/JBJS.RVW.15.00063. PMID: 27509329.","Hubbard AM. Imaging of pediatric hip disorders. Radiol Clin North Am. 2001 Jul;39(4):721-32. doi: 10.1016/s0033-8389(05)70307-9. PMID: 11549167."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84771"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84771"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-11T17:23:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T17:24:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4565"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"de